Under the support of this Career Award, the PI has made many contributions in advancing computational algorithms for quantum and statistical mechanics. 

Over the funding period, the PI has been highly product and accomplished more than 100 published papers in journal and conferences. The main research achievements on algorithm innovation and analysis, including the following hightlights: 

Frozen Gaussian approximation for surface hopping; 
Fast spectral method for half-space linear kinetic equations; 
Cooridnate descent algorithms for the full configuration interaction; 
Inchworm Monte Carlo method for open quantum systems; 
Sharp convergence rate estimate for hypocoercive sampling dynamics. 


Besides, during the project, the PI has co-authored a book "Mathematical Introduction to Electronic Structure Theory" and a review article "Numerical Methods for Kohn-Sham Density Functional Theory" which provide an applied mathematical introduction to the important field of electronic structure theory. 

Under the support of the grant, the PI has developed three new graduate courses covering topics ranging from stochastic control to computational methods for quantum many-body problems. The PI has also taught 3 mini-courses covering research topics related to the project, including concentration inequality, open quantum systems, and locality of quantum systems. In addition, the PI has given series of lectures in 3 summer schools on related topics. 

During the award, the PI has worked with 7 graduate students, 6 postdoctoral scholars, and many undergraduate and high school students partially funded by the project. 

The PI has successfully accomplished the goal of this project during its support. 



